{"title_page": "Maurice Mpolo", "text_new": "{{short description|Congolese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name   = Maurice Mpolo\n|image   = \n|office1  = Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]\n|term_start1  = 24 June 1960\n|term_end1  = 14 September 1960\n|president1  = [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]\n|predecessor1  = ''position established''\n|office2         = Member of the Chamber of Deputies<br>for [[Mai-Ndombe District|Lac L\u00e9opold II]]\n|term_start2     = 1960\n|term_end2       = 17 January 1961\n|birth_date  = 12 September 1928\n|birth_place  = [[Inongo]], [[Belgian Congo]]<br><small>(Now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congo-Kinshasa]])</small>\n|birth_name = \n|death_date  = 17 January 1961 (aged 32)\n|death_place  = Near [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], [[State of Katanga|Katanga]]<br><small>(Now [[Lubumbashi]])</small>\n|party   = [[Mouvement National Congolais]]\n}}\n'''Maurice Mpolo''' (12 September 1928 \u2013 17 January 1961) was a Congolese politician who served as Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] in 1960. He briefly led the Congolese army that July. He was executed alongside Prime Minister [[Patrice Lumumba]] in [[State of Katanga|Katanga]] in 1961.\n\n==Biography==\nMaurice Mpolo was born on 12 September 1928{{efn|According to Kashamura, Mpolo was born on 12 August.{{sfn|Kashamura|1966|p=86}} Heinz and Donnay state that he was born on 4 March.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}}} in [[Inongo]], [[Belgian Congo]].{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} His father was Alphonse Membe.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=391}} He had five years of primary education before studying as a novitiate for three years at the Fr\u00e9res des \u00c9coles Chr\u00e9tiennes \u00e0 Tumba.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} He later attended school in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] but was forced to drop out due to domestic problems.{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=111}} He became involved in several private enterprises and served in the colonial police force,{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} though he was dismissed from duty on 10 September 1952 after being repeatedly reprimanded for displaying arrogance and indiscipline.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} Mpolo also worked as a journalist and was arrested by the Belgian administration for publishing opinions they considered \"displaced\", though he was freed after an appeal.{{sfn|Brassinne|1989|loc=paragraph 163}} He eventually became the president of the L\u00e9opoldville chapter of the [[Mouvement National Congolais]] (MNC) and participated in the [[Belgo-Congolese Round Table Conference]] in [[Brussels]], Belgium on the organisation's behalf.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}\n\n=== Government career ===\n[[File:First Congolese government.jpg|thumb|The first Congolese government. Mpolo stands seventh from the right.]]\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote=\"Maurice Mpolo...was quick-tempered and daring, and his character gave the appearance of being hard. His youth had been very turbulent, and he had had much to suffer; among the young men of L\u00e9opoldville he was considered one of the tough ones. Shortly after leaving school, he had become a policeman, and was feared for the reputation he had then achieved as an intractable and merciless man to cross swords with.\"|source=[[Thomas Kanza]]'s reflection on Mpolo{{sfn|Kanza|1994|pp=111\u2013112}}}}\nWith the independence of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] in June 1960, Mpolo was elected to the [[National Assembly of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Chamber of Deputies]] as a representative from the [[Mai-Ndombe District|Lac L\u00e9opold II District]].{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} He was subsequently appointed by Prime Minister [[Patrice Lumumba]] to be Minister of Youth and Sports, effectively becoming the government's chief propagandist. He briefly stood in for General [[Victor Lundula]] as commander in chief of the [[Arm\u00e9e Nationale Congolaise]] (ANC) in July (earning the title of General) but got in a dispute with the army chief of staff, Colonel [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]].{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=198}} On 28 July Mpolo was made a member of a cabinet committee established to handle Congolese relations with [[United Nations]] officials.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=160}} On 13 September Lumumba declared him commander-in-chief of the ANC.{{sfn|G\u00e9rard-Libois|1966|p=143}}\n\nOn 14 September, Mobutu launched a coup which \"neutralised\" [[Lumumba Government|Lumumba's government]] and created a new one. Mpolo attempted to undermine it and rivaled Mobutu for control of the army.{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=198}} On 23 September, Mpolo and Deputy Prime Minister [[Antoine Gizenga]] were arrested and plans were made to send them to [[State of Katanga|secessionist Katanga]]. The [[United Nations]] (UN) put pressure on Mobutu to release them, which he did the following day.{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=115}} On 7 October, Lumumba announced that he had formed a new cabinet that included Mpolo as Minister of Defence. Mpolo told the press that he believed all of the conflicted parties in the central government would eventually unite. Angered by this, Mobutu dispatched troops to Mpolo's house, but he was nowhere to be found.{{sfn|FBIS|1960|p=100}} Later that day Mpolo was able to return to his home unmolested and requested that the UN strengthen its guard at his residence.{{sfn|FBIS|1960|p=101}}\n\n=== Arrest and death ===\nIn late November Lumumba fled the capital to organise [[Free Republic of the Congo|a new government]] in [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]]. He was captured before he could complete his escape and imprisoned at the army camp in [[Thysville]]. Mpolo also intended on reaching Stanleyville, but before he left he addressed a crowd of Lumumba's supporters at [[Lake Mai-Ndombe|Lac L\u00e9opold II]]. With Mobutu's government fearing Mpolo's potential to rally support for his cause, troops were dispatched to find him and arrested him in [[Mushie]]. He was later transferred to Thysville, along with Vice President of the Senate [[Joseph Okito]].{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=93}} On 17 January 1961, discipline in the base faltered and all three men were flown to [[\u00c9lisabethville]], Katanga. Once there, they were brutally tortured at the hands of [[Mo\u00efse Tshombe]] and [[Godefroid Munongo]], Lumumba's chief political rivals and the leaders of the secessionist state.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|pp=126\u2013127}} That night, one by one they were lined up against a tree to be executed by firing squad. Mpolo was the second to be shot.{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=120}}\n\nOn 17 January 2011, a [[Thanksgiving after Communion|mass of thanksgiving]] was held in memory of Mpolo and Okito at the Notre-Dame Cathedral in [[Kinshasa]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.radiookapi.net/actualite/2011/01/17/50eme-anniversaire-de-la-mort-de-lumumba-mpolo-et-okito-honores| title = 50\u00e8me anniversaire de l'assassinat de Lumumba: Mpolo et Okito honor\u00e9 | date = 17 January 2011| publisher = [[Radio Okapi]]| access-date = 12 January 2017| language = French}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Brassinne| first = Jacques| title = Les conseillers \u00e0 la Table ronde belgo-congolaise| journal = Courrier hebdomadaire du CRISP| issue = 1263-1264| pages = 1\u201362| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| location = Brussels| date = 1989| language = French| url = http://www.cairn.info/revue-courrier-hebdomadaire-du-crisp-1989-38-page-1.htm?1=1&DocId=27451| doi = 10.3917/cris.1263.0001| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| title = Daily Report: Foreign Radio Broadcasts, Issues 196\u2013200| publisher = [[Foreign Broadcast Information Service]]| date = 1960| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BU8jAQAAMAAJ&q=|ref= {{harvid|FBIS|1960}}}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Gerard | first1 = Emmanuel | last2 = Kuklick | first2 = Bruce | title = Death in the Congo: Murdering Patrice Lumumba| publisher = Harvard University Press| year = 2015| isbn = 978-0-674-72527-0 | location = Cambridge, MA| author2-link = Bruce Kuklick| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=G\u00e9rard-Libois|first=Jules|title=Katanga Secession|date=1966|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|edition=translated|oclc=477435|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch. Didier| title = The History of Congo | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| series = Greenwood histories of the modern nations| ISSN = 1096-2905| edition = illustrated, annotated| date = 2002| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780313316968| url-access = registration | isbn = 9780313316968|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Heinz| first = G.| last2 = Donnay| first2 = H.| title = Lumumba Patrice: les cinquante derniers jours de sa vie| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| date = 1976| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K_oMAQAAIAAJ&dq=| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Hoskyns| first = Catherine| title = The Congo Since Independence: January 1960 \u2013 December 1961| publisher = Oxford University Press| date = 1965| location = London| ref = harv| oclc= 414961}}\n* {{cite book| last = Kanza| first = Thomas R.| author-link = Thomas Kanza| title = The Rise and Fall of Patrice Lumumba: Conflict in the Congo| publisher = Schenkman Books, Inc.| edition = expanded| date = 1994| location = [[Rochester, Vermont]]| isbn = 0-87073-901-8| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Kashamura| first = Anicet| author-link = Anicet Kashamura| title = De Lumumba aux colonels| publisher = Buchet| date = 1966| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=14chAAAAMAAJ&q=| location= Paris| oclc = 465788990| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Omasombo| first = Jean Tshonda| last2 = Verhaegen| first2 = Beno\u00eet | title = Patrice Lumumba: acteur politique: de la prison aux portes du pouvoir, juillet 1956-f\u00e9vrier 1960| publisher = Harmattan| date = 2005| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dN0wAQAAIAAJ&focus=| isbn = 9782747563925| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = de Witte| first = Ludo| title = The Assassination of Lumumba| publisher = Verso| edition = illustrated| date = 2002| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bTdlU4yGB6YC&dq=| isbn = 9781859844106| ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Lumumba Government}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mpolo, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Mai-Ndombe Province]]\n[[Category:Mouvement National Congolais politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Lumumba Government members]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo military personnel]]\n[[Category:People murdered in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Democratic Republic of the Congo politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo torture victims]]\n[[Category:Executed Democratic Republic of the Congo people]]\n[[Category:People of the Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:1961 murders in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Congolese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name   = Maurice Mpolo\n|image   = \n|office1  = Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]\n|term_start1  = 24 June 1960\n|term_end1  = 14 September 1960\n|president1  = [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]\n|predecessor1  = ''position established''\n|office2         = Member of the Chamber of Deputies<br>for [[Mai-Ndombe District|Lac L\u00e9opold II]]\n|term_start2     = 1960\n|term_end2       = 17 January 1961\n|birth_date  = 12 September 1928\n|birth_place  = [[Inongo]], [[Belgian Congo]]<br><small>(Now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congo-Kinshasa]])</small>\n|birth_name = \n|death_date  = 17 January 1961 (aged 32)\n|death_place  = Near [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], [[State of Katanga|Katanga]]<br><small>(Now [[Lubumbashi]])</small>\n|party   = ''[[Mouvement National Congolais]]''\n}}\n'''Maurice Mpolo''' (12 September 1928 \u2013 17 January 1961) was a Congolese politician who served as Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] in 1960. He briefly led the Congolese army that July. He was executed alongside Prime Minister [[Patrice Lumumba]] in [[State of Katanga|Katanga]] in 1961.\n\n==Biography==\nMaurice Mpolo was born on 12 September 1928{{efn|According to Kashamura, Mpolo was born on 12 August.{{sfn|Kashamura|1966|p=86}} Heinz and Donnay state that he was born on 4 March.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}}} in [[Inongo]], [[Belgian Congo]].{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} His father was Alphonse Membe.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=391}} He had five years of primary education before studying as a novitiate for three years at the Fr\u00e9res des \u00c9coles Chr\u00e9tiennes \u00e0 Tumba.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} He later attended school in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] but was forced to drop out due to domestic problems.{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=111}} He became involved in several private enterprises and served in the colonial police force,{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} though he was dismissed from duty on 10 September 1952 after being repeatedly reprimanded for displaying arrogance and indiscipline.{{sfn|Omasombo|Verhaegen|2005|p=385}} Mpolo also worked as a journalist and was arrested by the Belgian administration for publishing opinions they considered \"displaced\", though he was freed after an appeal.{{sfn|Brassinne|1989|loc=paragraph 163}} He eventually became the president of the L\u00e9opoldville chapter of the ''[[Mouvement National Congolais]]'' (MNC) and participated in the [[Belgo-Congolese Round Table Conference]] in [[Brussels]], Belgium on the organisation's behalf.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}\n\n=== Government career ===\n[[File:First Congolese government.jpg|thumb|The first Congolese government. Mpolo stands seventh from the right.]]\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote=\"Maurice Mpolo...was quick-tempered and daring, and his character gave the appearance of being hard. His youth had been very turbulent, and he had had much to suffer; among the young men of L\u00e9opoldville he was considered one of the tough ones. Shortly after leaving school, he had become a policeman, and was feared for the reputation he had then achieved as an intractable and merciless man to cross swords with.\"|source=[[Thomas Kanza]]'s reflection on Mpolo{{sfn|Kanza|1994|pp=111\u2013112}}}}\nWith the independence of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] in June 1960, Mpolo was elected to the [[National Assembly of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Chamber of Deputies]] as a representative from the [[Mai-Ndombe District|Lac L\u00e9opold II District]].{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} He was subsequently appointed by Prime Minister [[Patrice Lumumba]] to be Minister of Youth and Sports, effectively becoming the government's chief propagandist. He briefly stood in for General [[Victor Lundula]] as commander in chief of the ''[[Arm\u00e9e Nationale Congolaise]]'' in July (earning the title of General) but got in a dispute with the army chief of staff, Colonel [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]].{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=198}} On 28 July Mpolo was made a member of a cabinet committee established to handle Congolese relations with [[United Nations]] officials.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=160}} On 13 September Lumumba declared him commander-in-chief of the ANC.{{sfn|G\u00e9rard-Libois|1966|p=143}}\n\nOn 14 September, Mobutu launched a coup which \"neutralised\" [[Lumumba Government|Lumumba's government]] and created a new one. Mpolo attempted to undermine it and rivaled Mobutu for control of the army.{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=198}} On 23 September, Mpolo and Deputy Prime Minister [[Antoine Gizenga]] were arrested and plans were made to send them to [[State of Katanga|secessionist Katanga]]. The [[United Nations]] (UN) put pressure on Mobutu to release them, which he did the following day.{{sfn|Gerard|Kuklick|2015|p=115}} On 7 October, Lumumba announced that he had formed a new cabinet that included Mpolo as Minister of Defence. Mpolo told the press that he believed all of the conflicted parties in the central government would eventually unite. Angered by this, Mobutu dispatched troops to Mpolo's house, but he was nowhere to be found.{{sfn|FBIS|1960|p=100}} Later that day Mpolo was able to return to his home unmolested and requested that the UN strengthen its guard at his residence.{{sfn|FBIS|1960|p=101}}\n\n=== Arrest and death ===\nIn late November Lumumba fled the capital to organise [[Free Republic of the Congo|a new government]] in [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]]. He was captured before he could complete his escape and imprisoned at the army camp in [[Thysville]]. Mpolo also intended on reaching Stanleyville, but before he left he addressed a crowd of Lumumba's supporters at [[Lake Mai-Ndombe|Lac L\u00e9opold II]]. With Mobutu's government fearing Mpolo's potential to rally support for his cause, troops were dispatched to find him and arrested him in [[Mushie]]. He was later transferred to Thysville, along with Vice President of the Senate [[Joseph Okito]].{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=93}} On 17 January 1961, discipline in the base faltered and all three men were flown to [[\u00c9lisabethville]], Katanga. Once there, they were brutally tortured at the hands of [[Mo\u00efse Tshombe]] and [[Godefroid Munongo]], Lumumba's chief political rivals and the leaders of the secessionist state.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|pp=126\u2013127}} That night, one by one they were lined up against a tree to be executed by firing squad. Mpolo was the second to be shot.{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=120}}\n\nOn 17 January 2011, a [[Thanksgiving after Communion|mass of thanksgiving]] was held in memory of Mpolo and Okito at the Notre-Dame Cathedral in [[Kinshasa]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.radiookapi.net/actualite/2011/01/17/50eme-anniversaire-de-la-mort-de-lumumba-mpolo-et-okito-honores| title = 50\u00e8me anniversaire de l'assassinat de Lumumba: Mpolo et Okito honor\u00e9 | date = 17 January 2011| publisher = [[Radio Okapi]]| access-date = 12 January 2017| language = French}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Brassinne| first = Jacques| title = Les conseillers \u00e0 la Table ronde belgo-congolaise| journal = Courrier hebdomadaire du CRISP| issue = 1263-1264| pages = 1\u201362| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| location = Brussels| date = 1989| language = French| url = http://www.cairn.info/revue-courrier-hebdomadaire-du-crisp-1989-38-page-1.htm?1=1&DocId=27451| doi = 10.3917/cris.1263.0001| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| title = Daily Report: Foreign Radio Broadcasts, Issues 196\u2013200| publisher = [[Foreign Broadcast Information Service]]| date = 1960| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BU8jAQAAMAAJ&q=|ref= {{harvid|FBIS|1960}}}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Gerard | first1 = Emmanuel | last2 = Kuklick | first2 = Bruce | title = Death in the Congo: Murdering Patrice Lumumba| publisher = Harvard University Press| year = 2015| isbn = 978-0-674-72527-0 | location = Cambridge, MA| author2-link = Bruce Kuklick| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=G\u00e9rard-Libois|first=Jules|title=Katanga Secession|date=1966|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|edition=translated|oclc=477435|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch.